Module 10 â€“ Standing Is Survival ğŸ§âš–ï¸
âš–ï¸ Core Message
Standing is not a technicality. It is the gateway to the courthouse. Without standing, the merits are never reached; with it, your claims can be heard.

ğŸ“– Lesson Content
â€¢ Standing as Gate ğŸšª â€” Show injury-in-fact: concrete, particularized, and actual or imminent.
â€¢ Standing as Link ğŸ”— â€” Show causation: the injury is fairly traceable to the defendantâ€™s conduct (not speculation).
â€¢ Standing as Remedy ğŸ¯ â€” Show redressability: the court can likely redress the harm with the relief you request (injunction, declaratory judgment, damages).
ğŸ“ Assignment
Draft a one-page Standing Statement to attach to a Complaint or motion for emergency relief. In three short sections (Injury-in-Fact, Causation, Redressability), state facts that satisfy each element. If seeking injunctive relief, include facts showing ongoing or imminent harm. Conclude with a 28 U.S.C. Â§ 1746 declaration.

âœ… Model Answer (Example)
PLAINTIFFâ€™S STANDING STATEMENT

In support of Plaintiffâ€™s Motion for Preliminary Injunction, Plaintiff states as follows:

Injury-in-Fact. Plaintiff has suffered concrete and particularized harm, including loss of employment opportunities and ongoing reputational injury arising from Defendantâ€™s actions on and after May 1, 2025. Plaintiff continues to face imminent harm absent court intervention.

Causation. The foregoing harms are fairly traceable to Defendantâ€™s conduct, including the issuance and continued enforcement of the challenged actions described in the accompanying Complaint (Â¶Â¶ 12â€“27).

Redressability. The requested reliefâ€”a preliminary injunction and declaratory judgmentâ€”will likely redress the harms by halting the challenged conduct, clarifying rights, and preventing further injury. Alternatively, damages at law will compensate past injury.

I declare under penalty of perjury that the foregoing is true and correct. 28 U.S.C. Â§ 1746.

Executed on [Date].
/s/ [Your Name]

ğŸ’¡ Reflection
Standing is a threeâ€‘legged stoolâ€”injury, causation, redressability. Remove any leg and the case falls. Pro se litigants should frontâ€‘load standing facts to prevent easy dismissal and to preserve appellate review.

ğŸ¨ Visual Pairing
Image Concept: A threeâ€‘legged stool labeled 'Injuryâ€‘inâ€‘Fact', 'Causation', and 'Redressability'. The stool stands firm only when all three legs are present. Caption: 'Standing Is Survival.'



