Module 11 â€“ Service Is Jurisdiction ğŸ“¬ğŸ§¾
âš–ï¸ Core Message
If service isnâ€™t perfected â€” and provable â€” the court may lack power to act on your papers. Service creates obligation, starts clocks, and anchors due process. Prove it in the record.

ğŸ“– Lesson Content
â€¢ Service as Trigger ğŸ¯ â€” Proper service (per FRCP 4/5 or state equivalents) creates the courtâ€™s power over parties and starts response deadlines.
â€¢ Service as Proof ğŸ“¸ â€” If you canâ€™t prove service, it didnâ€™t happen. File a Certificate of Service and attach receipts/affidavits (process server, certified mail, delivery logs, stipulated email).
â€¢ Service as Strategy ğŸ§  â€” Choose the ruleâ€‘compliant method thatâ€™s fastest and least disputable; get stipulations for email service; update addresses; use waiver where efficient.
ğŸ“ Assignment
Draft a Certificate of Service (COS) for your most recent filing. Include: (1) document served; (2) date/time; (3) names/addresses; (4) method with tracking/affidavit; (5) signature. Add an exhibit list for proof of service.

âœ… Model Answer (Example)
