Module 15 â€“ TROs Require Notice or Certification (FRCP 65(b)) ğŸ›ï¸ğŸ“‘
âš–ï¸ Core Message
Temporary Restraining Orders are extraordinary and shortâ€‘lived. Unless you give notice, FRCP 65(b) requires a written certification detailing your efforts to give notice and why notice should not be required. Missing this certification (or notice) can sink the TRO.

ğŸ“– Lesson Content
â€¢ Notice vs. Ex Parte ğŸ“£ â€” With notice: proceed under 65(a)/(b) and set a prompt hearing. Without notice (ex parte): you must submit specific facts showing immediate, irreparable injury and a written certification of efforts to give notice and why it should not be required.
â€¢ Specificity & Duration â±ï¸ â€” A TRO must state its terms specifically, describe the restrained acts, and generally expires after 14 days unless extended for good cause or by consent; the court should set a PI hearing at the earliest time.
â€¢ Security/Bond ğŸ’³ â€” Rule 65(c) typically requires security in an amount the court considers proper. Explain why a minimal bond (or none) is appropriate if applicable (public interest, indigency, or equitable factors).
â€¢ Local Rules & Format ğŸ§¾ â€” Follow local rules (caption, memorandum of law, proposed order, exhibits, and certificate of service). Attach declarations, key exhibits, and a narrowly tailored proposed order.
ğŸ“ Assignment
Assemble a TRO package:
1) Motion + memorandum applying Winter factors;
2) Declarations and exhibits proving immediacy and irreparable harm;
3) FRCP 65(b)(1)(B) Certification of notice efforts (if ex parte);
4) Proposed TRO + Proposed Order to Show Cause (PI hearing date);
5) Certificate of Service and, if required, a proposed bond amount.

âœ… Model Answer (Example)
RULE 65(b)(1)(B) CERTIFICATION OF NOTICE EFFORTS

I, [Your Name], certify as follows:

1. Efforts to Give Notice. On August 24, 2025 at 09:15 and 14:30, I emailed and called counsel for Defendant ([email@firm.com], (555) 555â€‘5555) regarding Plaintiffâ€™s intended TRO filing. I left voicemail messages and requested a sameâ€‘day meetâ€‘andâ€‘confer. I received no response. I also sent a copy of the TRO package via email to [secondary contact] at 18:05.

2. Why Notice Should Not Be Required. Immediate and irreparable harm will occur before an adversarial hearing can be held: Defendant plans to [imminent action] within 24 hours, which would cause nonâ€‘compensable injury to Plaintiffâ€™s constitutional rights and professional standing. Providing additional notice risks precipitating the very harm sought to be prevented.

3. Attachments. Exhibits include email timestamps (Ex. A), call logs (Ex. B), and a sworn declaration detailing urgency (Ex. C).

I declare under penalty of perjury that the foregoing is true and correct. 28 U.S.C. Â§ 1746.

Executed on August 25, 2025.
/s/ [Your Name]

ğŸ’¡ Reflection
Ex parte relief is the rare exception. Credibility and completeness carry the day: a specific, wellâ€‘documented certification, narrow relief, and a fast path to a PI hearing make a TRO request viable and appealâ€‘proof.

ğŸ¨ Visual Pairing
Image Concept: A clock marked '14 days' next to a oneâ€‘page sheet stamped '65(b) Certification,' both clipped to a Proposed Order. Caption: 'No notice? Then certify.'



