Tier 2 â€” Lawfare Resistance
Module 16 (Revised) â€“ Motions Must State Grounds & Relief with Particularity (FRCP 7(b)) ğŸ§±ğŸ–Šï¸
âš–ï¸ Core Message
Courts deny vague requests. Federal Rule of Civil Procedure 7(b)(1) requires a written motion that states (1) the specific grounds with record support and (2) the precise relief requested. Particularity turns a plea into a decisionâ€‘ready order.

ğŸ“– Lesson Content
â€¢ Two Parts of Particularity âœŒï¸ â€” (A) Grounds: cite the rule/statute/case and pinâ€‘cite the record (Exs., Â¶Â¶, ECF Nos.). (B) Relief: draft exactly what the order should say, in numbered â€˜IT IS ORDEREDâ€™ clauses.
â€¢ Decisionâ€‘Ready Packet ğŸ“¦ â€” Include: Points & Authorities (if required), declaration(s), exhibits, proposed order, certificate of service, and a meetâ€‘andâ€‘confer statement where local rules require it.
â€¢ Format to Win ğŸ§­ â€” Use headings, short paragraphs, bullets, and prejudice/harmlessness analysis. Avoid adjectives; lead with facts. Give the court a narrow, administrable remedy.
â€¢ Cure by Leave ğŸ©¹ â€” If you need to supplement, file late, or exceed a limit, seek leave. Show good cause or excusable neglect; attach the proposed filing as Exhibit 1 so the judge can grant and docket in one step.
â€¢ Respect Local Rules ğŸ“œ â€” Page limits, font/margins, hearing requests, reply timing, conferral requirementsâ€”mirror them in your motion.
ğŸ“ Assignment
Rewrite the vague request â€œPlease reconsider and let me file moreâ€ into a twoâ€‘page Rule 7(b) motion titled <b>Motion for Leave to File Supplemental Reply</b> that includes: (1) Issue & Requested Relief; (2) Grounds (new authority/new fact + good cause); (3) Prejudice/Harmlessness; (4) Proposed Order; (5) Meetâ€‘andâ€‘Confer; (6) Certificate of Service. Attach the proposed supplemental reply as Exhibit 1.

